<DOC><DOCNO> AP880623-0206 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-88 1952EST</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-23 0303</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0310</SECOND><HEAD>More Heat; Scattered Storms in Upper Mississippi Valley, Northeast</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A cool front brought some relief from the heat Thursday in partsof the Northeast and mid-Atlantic states, but most of the nation'smidsection continued to swelter and suffer.   Afternoon readings were already in the mid-90s to around 100degrees from the central high Plains through the lower MissouriValley into the Tennessee Valley and mid-Atlantic states.   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered Thursday afternoonacross the upper Mississippi Valley, the strongest one movingacross parts of southeastern South Dakota and northeastern Nebraska.   Thunderstorms were also scattered along a Canadian cold frontthat was sagging south across the northern mid-Atlantic region.   Showers and thunderstorms, accompanied by gusty winds and heavyrain, were widespread along the Gulf of Mexico coast into Florida.There were also isolated storms across the deserts of SouthernCalifornia.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 53degrees at Nashua, N.H., to 109 at Phoenix and Glendale, Ariz. Theearly morning low for the nation was 40 at Truckee, Calif.   The national forecast for Friday called for continued sunny andhot weather across much of the nation. Scattered showers andthunderstorms were predicted across the Great Lakes into parts ofIowa; from southern Texas across the Gulf Coast into the southernAtlantic Coast and much of Florida; and in parts of the desertSouthwest and Great Basin.   Highs will be in the 70s along the California coast and fromUpper Michigan through much of New England; 80s across the PacificNorthwest and from the Great Lakes into the mid-Atlantic states;between 100 and 105 across the central Plains; above 105 in theSouthern California valleys and the desert Southwest; and in the90s across most of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>